result.adr_address: Ma On Shan Promenade, Sai Kung, Hong Kong
result.formatted_address: Ma On Shan Promenade, Sai Kung, Hong Kong
result.name: Sai Kung Waterfront Promenade

reviews.text: Lots of doggies on the weekend. It's relaxing. You can take a boat to most nearby islands /beaches (from around 30 to 150 hkd). Also, beware of pick pockets!

The Promenade is hive of activity in Sai Kung with some interesting things to see (and taste). In addition to the large Cantonese seafood restaurants and a couple of bars, you will find sampan boat for private hire as well as boat service to area islands and beaches.

Most interestingly, however, the promenade is the scene of a floating seafood market that is quite unique to see. Here you will find quite a few boats mooring along the promenade offering a wide variety of fresh seafood which they sell direct to the customers lingering above on the piers.

It is a very interesting scene to witness. Fisherman negotiate directly with the crowd, When deals are made, boaters descale and fillet fresh fish right on the boat or bag the fish whole depending on what customers desire. Lots of shellfish and exotic seafood like octopi and starfish available as well.

From their moored boats, fisherman send the seafood purchases up in nets to the customers waiting upon the piers. Payment is are then sent down in the same nets. It is sensible yet interesting way of conducting transactions. You almost want to buy something just to try.

You can see the floating seafood market at the Sai Kung Promenade all week. On weekends it can be crowded. However, boats are usually in greater numbers as well, meaning you have more to see and more opportunity for neat photographs as well.
The rare places that can see human and pets living nicely.
Good for relaxation

result.adr_address: 新界 惠 民 路, Wai Man Rd, Sai Kung, Hong Kong
result.formatted_address: 新界 惠 民 路, Wai Man Rd, Sai Kung, Hong Kong
result.name: Sai Kung Waterfront Park

reviews.text:
Went here on a weekend and there were lots of people walking and milling around the park. The greenery and pavillion is adjacent to the bus terminus and it has public toilets. 

It is a nice place to unwind with the breeze coming from the sea.  The promenade and pier in front provides opportunity for strolling dogs. Many fishermen on their boats offer their fresh catch to people wishing to buy them for cooking later. Tour operators pitch their trips to the outlying islands via handheld PA system.

Sai King Harbour front is a short walk up and down but with some nice things to see. The area is one of the few places I found where many come to walk their dogs. The pier offers a wide variety of boat tours for tourists. These can take you round to show you a unique view of the local UNESCO Geopark. You can also buy fresh seafood if you were interested or try some at one of the local seafood restaurants.

Somehow I was invited to this seafood restaurant very famous on the waterfront of SaiKung and we heard that it was run by the Triad.??!! When we entered we were lead to VIP booth up in second floor, it was actually pretty intimidating and lots of higher class(?) clientele on top. I was very under dressed as we had planned to go hiking at the MacLehose Trail. XD OPPS!!!??? Also, I hate seafood, but this place actually had some good tofu/veggies.

Nice place for responsible owners to enjoy walking with your dog, spectacular view, nice smell of nature and great interaction with people around here. Lots of choices on food, lawns to share with public including doggies and strayed cows
Sai kung is a very good place to go out of the city centre
